-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We advise and represent clients with disabilities (adults and children) and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">sometimes </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">their carers regarding their entitlement to assessments and services from local authorities and NHS agencies. We also specialise in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> mental incapacity law and are regularly instructed by the Official Solicitor to the Supreme Court (a branch of the Ministry of Justice) in vulnerable adult protection cases</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and challenges to deprivation of liberty under the Mental Capacity Act</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. These case</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s often concern the protection of adults at risk of abuse or neglect, and involve statutory agencies and other family members in complex legal and factual disputes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This short submission is intended to focus on how the Government’s further proposals to re</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">duce legal aid will impact</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> adversely</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> on the client group we serve, namely disabled people.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> These include people </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">with:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mental illness</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">/disorder</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">learning disabilities</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">autism/Asperger’s syndrome</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">head injuries</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">physical disabilities</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">terminal illness such as ca</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">cer</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">progressive illnesses such as dementia etc.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Submissions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is important to note that these new proposals come only days after implementation of LASPOA on 1 April 2013, which is the most extensive reform to the legal aid system for many years. The true effect of LASPOA has yet to be assessed however already ther</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e is evidence that numbers of the public seeking and obtaining legal advice </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">have dramatically reduced. This may be partly because of the practical difficulties faced by clients in finding a suitable adviser who is still offering legal aid services but also</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> because of the barriers to accessing and evidencing eligibility for legal aid.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There are very few community care legal advisers left offering a service. We are all extremely busy and have to turn clients away on a daily basis. We think that these clients</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> will not be able to obtain advice elsewhere and many have already been through the list of existing advisers before they come to us. Many clients are at the end of their tether and if we cannot help them, are distraught.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are three main proposals wh</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ich will adversely affect disabled and mentally incapacitated people – the residence test, the judicial review changes and the removal of legal aid from prisoners.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The residence test</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">All clients seeking legal advice will have to meet the residence test. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">For our clients this will be particularly difficult because of their disabilities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is obvious but worth restating that the effect of removing legal aid</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> advice and representation for any client who (a) does not meet the residence test or (b) cannot prov</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e that they meet the residence test</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> will be disastrous. We can think of one practical example of a client who may well not have met the residence test, and this illustrates the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">practical effect on one person.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We acted for ‘P’ in a Court of Protection case</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. P’s family had come from Pakistan to the UK. P had learning disabilities. He lived with his family. He attended a day centre. Staff were concerned because when he arrived he started to rummage in the bins and looking for food because he had not been fed.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> They also noticed that he had evidence of severe bruising. It was discovered that he was being kept in a concrete shed in the yard of the family home, like a dog, and being regularly beaten by the family. He was being starved. He wanted to leave. We repre</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">sented him in Court to remove him from his family home into a supported living project where he could be fed and was safe. The application was vigorously contested by his family who wanted to keep him at home because they would have access to his benefits.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> The Judge decided that he should not be returned to the family.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is entirely possible that our client would not have met the residence test. Is it really envisaged that such a vulnerable person, without mental capacity, should be denied protection from</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> such abuse and neglect?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This case would not have been exempt from the test because the client was not being detained. In fact most of our clients are arguably detained in care homes and hospitals but this is not being lawfully authorised under either the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Mental Capacity Act or the Mental Health Act. The definition of ‘detention’ under the Mental Capacity Act is in itself hotly disputed and the subject of litigation in the Supreme Court this autumn. The exemption due to ‘detention’ is not currently defined</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> but we think it will simply not apply to most if not all of our clients, and will not resolve the underlying problem with the test.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">For those who meet the residence test, the problem will be that of proof. Most if not all of our clients have never had a passport. This is because if you are disabled from birth you are less likely to have access to funds and less likely to have been abro</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ad. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">By definition, disabled people are more likely to need to access legal advice because of the problems they face but also because they are more likely to be eligible on the legal aid means test.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We cannot think of how most of our clients would be able </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to meet the two stage residence test. They do not have company accounts, they are less likely to have children or have been employed, so there is not the same paper trail as there would be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">for other groups. It is going to be very difficult if not impossibl</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e for our clients to prove that they meet the test and for us, as legal aid practitioners, to administer it. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The result will be that we will be deterred from accepting instructions unless we have full paperwork. This will mean that clients who meet the t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">est will be turned away. This is not because we are unable to help them but because of the application of the test. In our view, many extremely vulnerable people will be facing destitution, risk of abuse and neglect, and physical/mental harm as a result.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Judicial review</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We have taken some of the leading judicial review cases in the field of community care and health care law. For example, we were instructed in the ‘Coughlan’ case wh</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ich concerned the responsibilities</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of the NHS to provide long term healthc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are, a decision which has benefited many thousands of people who have been wrongly charged for healthcare</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in nursing homes and other settings</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We were also instructed in the House of Lords case concerning the legality of charging mental patients for their</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> mental health aftercare services</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> under s.117 Mental Health Act 1983</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. That case has also benefited hundreds of thousands of vulnerable people and ensured that society has </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">cared for the most severely mentally ill persons, reducing the risk of harm to themse</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">lves and to the public.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In addition we have taken many cases concerning the closure of small mental health longstay hospitals (following the closure of the old style asylums many smaller units were built), and care homes for older people.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> These can involv</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e acting for 20 or 30 people because the effect of moving each client will be different and depend on their individual characteristics, whether they have mental capacity etc.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">All of these types of cases</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> therefore</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> involve an enormous amount of work to prep</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are initially, following the pre action protocol process. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The more complex the case, the more there is a lengthy history, the more work which is required initially. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The nature of judicial review litigation is such that it is geared towards all the work </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">being done in the very early stages of the case, in preparing for issuing proceedings. It is this work which is now ‘at risk’ under the Government’s proposals. The concession that the Legal Aid Agency may exercise its discretion</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (at the end of the case)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> pay costs in cases which settle pre permission does not save the scheme – the simple fact is that we cannot risk taking such cases in future because of the risk of not being paid.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Years of underfunding of legal aid means that we cannot afford to take more</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> risks.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Permission is not always a true reflection of the merit of the case. Views depend on the Judge on the day and are not always consistent. We have had some cases where permission has been refused yet granted on renewal/appeal. These cases will not b</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e brought at all in future because of the lack of payment.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is the Legal Aid Agency which is responsible for granting legal aid. It must apply the criteria and assess the merit. This is the correct filtering mechanism for unmeritorious cases, added to w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hich the Judge considering permission could, in refusing permission, decide that the case is wholly without merit. These are sufficient safeguards.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The effect of the proposal will be that the more complicated community care cases will not be brought at al</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">l because the greater the complexity, the greater the risk to the firm of bringing the case. At the same time, those cases which are issued will be pushed to permission and settlement will be less likely because of the costs issue. This all creates unneces</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">sary and unhelpful perverse incentives in litigation which is all about holding the state to account by its citizens.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Prisoners</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Whilst we do not undertake prison law, we deplore the proposal to remove legal aid from the vast majority of prison cases. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Prison is a closed institution, like many of the hospitals and care homes we work in, and we know only too well from our clients how intimidating it can be to feel that there is no external scrutiny of what goes on inside. Closing off that access to extern</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">al independent advice will result in great risk of abuse of power.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A disproportionate number of prisoners have mental health needs. Many are also elderly</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and have health problems</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, and recent reports in the press have </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">emphasis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ed the lack of proper faciliti</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">es for caring for physically and mentally frail prisoners. We are greatly concerned by the impact of removing legal aid for disabled prisoners precisely because they are faced with not only being in a closed environment but they are also least able to exer</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">cise the remaining rights which they have, and find it most difficult to enforce rights to care and health care.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Conclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">These proposals are intended to remove legal aid from the most vulnerable and to prevent the State and its agencies to be challeng</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ed. If implemented, they will</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> certainly have that effect. The real losers will of course be those who need the advice the most and for whom access to legal advice really matters. Of all those people, disabled and mentally ill people will be least able to p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rotect themselves and are those to whom society owes the greatest obligation to protect.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">27 September 2013</span></p></div></body></html>